# GameNative — Smart Game Config: Auto-Apply & Override Layers

The app must **never** require the user to manually set Proton/Wine versions, DX wrapper,
or compatibility flags to get a known game running. `KnownGameFixes` is the authoritative
database of "what this game needs." Every launch pipeline must enforce those requirements
automatically — even for containers created before the fix was added.

---

## The Problem We Are Solving

GameHub makes users manually pick Proton 9 vs 10, enable/disable fsync, set WINEDLLOVERRIDES
for every game they want to play. That is the core reason this project exists. We must never
replicate that UX failure.

Every game in `KnownGameFixes` must boot correctly on first launch with zero user interaction.
If the game needs Proton 9 and the container already has Proton 10, we migrate it automatically
at launch. If a WINEDLLOVERRIDE is required to prevent a crash, it is applied unconditionally.

---

## Config Layer Stack — Priority (lowest → highest)

```
1. ContainerData defaults (from PrefManager / DefaultVersion)
        ↓
2. KnownGameFixes.protonVersion  (auto-migrates container.wineVersion)
        ↓
3. GameConfigRecommender         (hardware-optimal settings: DXVK, VKD3D, Box64 tuning)
        ↓
4. CrashRecoveryManager          (downgrades after repeated crashes)
        ↓
5. AdaptivePrelaunchTuner        (momentary thermal/memory pressure reduction)
        ↓
6. KnownGameFixes.extraEnvVars   (ALWAYS re-applied last in applyGameConfig — never skipped)
        ↓
7. GameProfileOverrides          (explicit user choice — compatibilityLayerVersionId etc.)
```

**Higher number = higher priority.** User's explicit manual choice (#7) beats everything.
KnownGameFixes env vars (#6) beat a stale saved GameConfig. KnownGameFixes protonVersion (#2)
beats whatever the container was created with, unless the user explicitly overrode it (#7).

---

## Where Each Thing Is Enforced

### Container.wineVersion (which Wine binary launches)

**File:** `app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/utils/ContainerUtils.kt`

`applyPerGameContainerOverrides()` is the single choke-point before every launch. It now
applies KnownGameFixes **before** the user-override layer:

```kotlin
fun applyPerGameContainerOverrides(context, appId, containerData): ContainerData {
    var result = containerData

    // Layer 2: KnownGameFixes protonVersion (baseline, auto-migrate)
    val knownFixVersion = resolveKnownFixWineVersion(context, appId)
    if (knownFixVersion != null && result.wineVersion != knownFixVersion) {
        Timber.i("KnownGameFix: migrating wineVersion → $knownFixVersion for $appId")
        result = result.copy(wineVersion = knownFixVersion)
    }

    // Layer 7: user's explicit pick wins
    val overrides = GameProfileStore.load(context, appId) ?: return result
    if (overrides.compatibilityLayerVersionId != null) {
        result = result.copy(wineVersion = overrides.compatibilityLayerVersionId)
    }
    ...
}
```

`resolveKnownFixWineVersion(context, appId)` maps `ProtonVersion` enum → installed version
identifier string (`"proton-9.0-arm64ec"`) by scanning `ContentsManager.getProfiles(PROTON)`.
Returns null if the game has no KnownGameFix, the fix has no protonVersion requirement, or
the required version is not installed (in which case no migration happens and the user must
download it first via the Compatibility Layer screen).

### Env vars (WINEDLLOVERRIDES, DXVK_ASYNC, etc.)

**File:** `app/src/main/java/app/gamenative/launch/LaunchOrchestrator.kt`

`applyGameConfig()` **always** re-applies `KnownGameFixes.extraEnvVars` last, even if the
caller has a saved GameConfig with different values. This is unconditional — no "if fix exists"
guard is needed; the loop is a no-op when the fix map is empty.

### GameConfig.protonVersion (informational / UI)

`resolveGameConfig()` re-applies `KnownGameFixes.protonVersion` in-memory when loading a
saved config. This keeps the version picker's "Recommended" badge accurate even when the
stored config was generated before the fix was added. The re-applied value is **not written
back to disk** — the stored config is only updated when the recommender runs (first launch) or
the user presses "Recommended."

